# scripts/check-dist-drift.mjs compares committed dist/ against a fresh build BYTE-FOR-BYTE
# (sha256 per file), so git must never rewrite line endings on anything that comparison touches.
#
# Without this, on Windows (core.autocrlf=true, the installer default) git checks dist/ out with
# CRLF while `wxt build` writes LF. The drift check then reports "dist/ is stale" on a FRESH
# CLONE, with no source change whatsoever — and the two gates become unsatisfiable at the same
# time: check:dist passes only when the working tree holds LF, `git status` is clean only when it
# holds CRLF. That lands on the first line of ACCEPTANCE.md ("local gates pass and dist is in
# sync"), so the team test would open on a failure that is not a failure.
#
# The build's INPUTS matter as much as its outputs: WXT copies public/ and the entrypoint HTML
# into dist/ verbatim, so a CRLF *input* produces a CRLF dist file and the drift survives
# rebuilding. Observed on options.html — a fresh build emitted `</div>\r\r\n  </body>` where the
# commit has `</div>\n  </body>`. Measured 2026-07-19/20: with endings normalised, the committed
# and freshly built files are byte-identical.
#
# ADR 0017 accepted a committed dist/ with a drift check as the guard; pinning the tree to LF is
# that guard's own platform assumption, made explicit, and makes the build reproducible across
# the team's machines.

# Pin the whole working tree to LF for a reproducible cross-machine build.
* text=auto eol=lf

# Build output, hashed by the drift check — never convert.
dist/** -text

# Copied verbatim into dist/ by WXT, including the vendored/binary ONNX Runtime pair — never convert.
public/** -text
